so then, for users and groups also has permissions and roles?

### **Do Users and Groups Have Permissions and Roles?**  

ğŸ‘‰ **Users and Groups in AWS IAM do NOT have roles, but they have permissions through policies.**  

---

### **1ï¸âƒ£ IAM Users (Individual Access)**
âœ… Represents an **individual person** (e.g., a developer, admin).  
âœ… Uses **long-term credentials** (passwords, access keys).  
âœ… Does **not assume roles** (unless explicitly allowed).  
âœ… Needs **policies attached** to define what they can do.  

ğŸ“Œ **Example:**  
- A **developer IAM user** has a policy that allows access to an S3 bucket.  
- This policy grants the user read/write permissions.  

---

### **2ï¸âƒ£ IAM Groups (Multiple Users with Same Permissions)**
âœ… A **group is a collection of IAM users**.  
âœ… Groups help **manage multiple users' permissions** at once.  
âœ… Policies are attached to **groups**, and all users in the group inherit those permissions.  
âœ… Groups **CANNOT assume roles** (only users and services can assume roles).  

ğŸ“Œ **Example:**  
- A **"Developers" group** has a policy allowing access to EC2 and S3.  
- Any user added to this group automatically gets the same permissions.  

---

### **3ï¸âƒ£ IAM Roles (For AWS Services & Cross-Account Access)**
âœ… Roles are for **AWS services, federated users, or external accounts**.  
âœ… Cannot be directly assigned to a user or group.  
âœ… Roles need to be **assumed** (e.g., an EC2 instance assumes a role to access S3).  
âœ… Use **temporary credentials** (not long-term passwords or access keys).  

ğŸ“Œ **Example:**  
- An EC2 instance assumes a role to access S3 **without needing access keys**.  

---

### **Key Differences:**
| Feature         | IAM Users  | IAM Groups | IAM Roles |
|---------------|-----------|------------|-----------|
| **Who uses it?** | Individual person | Collection of users | AWS services, external users/accounts |
| **Can have policies?** | âœ… Yes | âœ… Yes (affects all users in the group) | âœ… Yes (must attach policies) |
| **Can assume roles?** | âŒ No (unless explicitly allowed) | âŒ No | âœ… Yes |
| **Uses long-term credentials?** | âœ… Yes (passwords, access keys) | âœ… Yes (via user accounts) | âŒ No (uses temporary credentials) |
| **Best Use Case** | Human users logging into AWS | Managing permissions for multiple users | Giving AWS services permissions without access keys |

---

### **Final Answer:**
ğŸ”¹ **Users and Groups have permissions via policies, but they DO NOT have roles.**  
ğŸ”¹ **Roles are meant for AWS services or external access, not individual users.**  
ğŸ”¹ **Users can assume roles (if allowed), but roles do not belong to users.**  

